<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-557-802  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 557 802.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  June 18 1990 n1448* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Matsushita's erasable optical disk is all-optical. (MatsushitaElectric Industrial Company Ltd.'s Panasonic LF 7010 optical diskdrive) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Matsushita Electric Industrial Company Ltd. (product introduction)Energy Conversion Devices Inc. (licenses).andO;Ticker:    MC; ENER.andO;Product:   Panasonic LF-7010 (Optical disk drive) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionOptical DisksErasable Optical Memory.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MATSUSHITA's ERASABLE OPTICAL DISK IS ALL-OPTICALandM;In the mid-1980s, Japanese companies came out with a string of announcementsof &quot;breakthroughs&quot; in the development of erasable optical media, but so far,we have seen in products only the magneto-optic technique that wasessentially perfected much earlier.andP;  Now, reports Microbytes Daily,Matsushita Electric Industrial Co has come out with an erasable drive thatuses an all-optical technology that measures the change in phase of lightreflected from the recorded spot.andP;  Although phase change technology does notimprove the access time over magneto-optic, it requires only a single pass torecord a bit, where with magneto-optic, the previous bit must first beerased, and once the new one has been written, it must be verified.andP;  With thephase change technology - Matsushita is licensing it from Energy ConversionDevices Inc, Troy, Michigan - the disk medium includes a thin layer ofmaterial that changes with the application of laser light from a highlyreflective crystalline state to a dull amorphous state depending ontemperature, retaining either state when it cools, so that bits can beswitched between the two states to create zeros and ones.andP;  Panasonic'smedium, which stores 1Gb - 500Mb per side - on a 5.25&quot; platter - is claimedto withstand 100,000 writes, or 1m with error detection and correction.andP;  Theaverage access time is 90mS but the disk transfers at 10Mbits per second, andthe SCSI-2 transfer rate can reach 4M-bytes per second.andP;  Panasonic - thetrade name under which Matsushita will market the drives - expects theLF-7010 to be available in November at $5,000.andP;  The thing can also read - andwrite once, the 940Mb disks used in the LF-5010 write-once disk drive.andO;</TEXT></DOC>